Install, configure, troubleshoot, and d-c-a prep.

You've come the whole way, from, what is a container, to a hardened, orchestrated cluster. This final module is the operator's half of the story: standing Docker up properly, configuring the daemon, and debugging it when things break, plus how to turn all of it into a d-c-a certification. Where the earlier modules built up the platform, this one steps back down to the engine at the center of the map: the docker daemon, container-d, and run-see, the daemon stack that everything else rides on.

The module runs in three movements.

First, install and configure. The right way to install Docker Engine, from the official repositories, not the distro's stale package. The post-install steps that make it pleasant to use, like the docker group, and enabling it on boot. And the one file that tunes the daemon, slash e-t-c slash docker slash daemon dot j-son, covering storage, logging, and runtime drivers.

Second, troubleshoot. A repeatable method for the three things that break: the daemon won't start, a container or a build misbehaves, or the network won't pass packets. Each one has a small, memorable set of first commands.

Third, certify. What the d-c-a exam actually tests, what to memorise versus look up, and where to go next, like Kubernetes and the cloud certs.

So the arc is: install, then configure with daemon dot j-son, which sets up the docker-daemon, container-d, run-see stack, then troubleshoot it, then certify. The final section is a synthesis: the six d-c-a domains map one-to-one onto modules one through nine, so preparing for the exam is really just consolidating the course you've already done. By the end, you can install, configure, debug, and certify. A working Docker operator.
